Port 80  Httpd
Enum
Simple dynamic dns provider page.
Provides domain names for ip addresses.
Provide a ip address and it will assign a domain name.
Useful info
 API used is the same as another dns provider called → no-ip.com
 3 hostnames are provided by the service .
 Username and password for getting the service.
Exploiting the api

some documentation related to its api which we can use to work here.

Exploitation
Now since this website is under work , it may have many flaws , so it is a
basic api pentest rule to check for rce in the functions.
Here we can clearly see that some command is being run by using our input
as variable.
And if the code is not well written then there is a chance that the inputs are
not properly sanitized.
In order to check this ,
We can assume that a bash command is being run .
Our inputs are also checked like : hostname can contain only three of
those domains and the ip should be a valid ip.
INjecting some command via ip is tough because it is checking for
numbers and we cant inject command just using numbers.
SO the only option left is to inject command in the sub domain
section of the hostname.As that is the section that can include any
special character and doesnt seem to care a bit to throw a error.
This means if the command is something like this :

Privesc
bindmgr user
There is a user named bindmgr .
His home directory has a folder that is readable by everyone.
And from one of the files → strace.txt we get a private ssh key.
When tried to ssh it does not allow to log in.
This means there are some extra sets of protections.
SO when the public key was checked , we can find that that ssh from
certain sub domain is only allowed.
And for us to login in as bindmgr our ip needs to be identified under that
sub domain.
Reverse dns lookup is used to check whether the ip from which ssh login
is originating is present in the ptr records as *.infra.dyna.htb.
When the server carries out a ptr record check(THese records store infos
about domains) , we will not have a record under the wildcard
*.infra.dyna.htb.
Because of which we will disallowed login.
Adding A and PTR record for our ip
To make this work we need to add A and PTR record for our ip so that when
the server checks both A and PTR records we have our entries.
This can be done with the help of nsupdate command.
nsupdate -k /etc/bind/infra.key
nsupdate -k /etc/bind/infra.key

The final privesc would be root and there is a direct vector for it in sudo -l
bindmgr.sh analysis
 bindmgr.sh is used to create config files.
 IN order for it to run perfectly we need to add some files.
This line checks whether there is a file called .version in the dir that we
are running the sudo.
 So create a file named .version and satisfy the check.
One can use strace to find which exit number the program is using to exit
the process.
Then it checks whether the number in the file .version is less than the
number in /etc/bin/named.bindmgr/.version .
 SO we need to add a number to the .version file such as 5.
The next few code adds a include line to /etc/bind/named.conf.bindmgr .

The following line copies everything in the current directory and places
them in the /etc/bin/named.bindmgr .
This is the code that can be exploited.
As soon as one sees a relative path in a script one should make sure to try
to exploit it.
In normal scripts if absolute path is not mentioned in the case of
predefined binaries like cat <some file> instead of /usr/bin/cat
<some file> THEN WE CAN DO PATH HIJACK ATTACK AND GAIN
CONTROL OVER CAT BINARY.
But in this case sudo is being used with a env reset which means we
cant do that.
But in case of cp command rather than using absolute path the script uses
just the wildcard * .
There is a parameter in cp that lets u preserve the permissions of a file
while copying from one directory to another directory with different umask .
→ More about umask:CONCEPTS ONLY  umask DYNSTR
Strategy
We will place a copy of the bash binary in our current directory and give it a
suid bit.
chmod
chmod
+s
+s
bash
bash
Note: If we run the sudo command now then the bash binary will be
copied to the /etc/bin/named.bindmgr but the permissions will be
changed and the binary will no longer have the suid bit set.
Since the script copies all the files from the current working dir and pastes
them in another dir , it will also copy a file name by the name '--
preserve=mode'.
Hence create a file named --preserve=mode
echo
echo
""
""

this.

/etc/bind/named.bindmgr
This command will make sure to copy all the files and paste them with their
orginal permissions , in this manner our bash binary will have the suid bit set
and since the sudo is being run by root it will also have a root ownership.
This means that we can get a effective root id shell using the argument -p .
We are effective root
Post exploit
Complete root access
The shell that we got was just a partial root shell , we were able to read files
but cannot write any of the files with root permission on it.
SO in order to get a root shell we could use a simple python script as
follows that will set the uid as 0 and then spawn a sh shell :

But running this returns a permission denied:
How is this possible ? Since suid bit is set it must be able to run the setuid
functionas root rt?
The answer is no.It is because of a special security principle that linux
follows → linux doesnt allow scripts to be run as root even if suid bit is set
for the script.
It only runs as the user that runs it.
But there is a way around this.
 One could create a simple compiled c file that sets the uid as 0 and then
calls /bin/bash .

But this method cannot be used in this system as there is no gcc installed.

 One could ssh into bindmgr because of two loopholes:
Directories and log files inside bindmgr was world readable
 Change the permissions and make it only readable by bindmgr.
infra.key was also readable.
 Make it readable only by bindmgr.
 Root was compromised becasue of the use of relative path to copy thr files
from a directory that could be accessed by anyone.
 While using cp command use absolute path so that the filename will also
be considered as a file and be copied rather than becoming an argument.
Changed script:

rather than this:
cp .version bash --preserve=mode /etc/bin/named.bindmgr
